ally {\\n            reader.close()\\n        }\\n        assertTrue(file.getText('UTF-8').contains('new-writer'))\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void traversesAndMatchesDirectoryContentsUsingPathExtensionMethods(@TempDir Path tempDir) {\\n        Path root = tempDir.resolve('root')\\n        Path child = root.resolve('child')\\n        Path other = root.resolve('other')\\n        Files.createDirectories(child)\\n        Files.createDirectories(other)\\n        child.resolve('alpha.txt').text = 'alpha'\\n        child.resolve('skip.log').text = 'skip'\\n        other.resolve('beta.txt').text = 'beta'\\n        root.resolve('top.txt').text = 'top'\\n\\n        List<String> immediateFiles = []\\n        root.eachFile(FileType.FILES) { Path path -> immediateFiles << path.fileName.toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['top.txt'], immediateFiles.sort())\\n\\n        List<String> immediateDirs = []\\n        root.eachDir { Path path -> immediateDirs << path.fileName.toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['child', 'other'], immediateDirs.sort())\\n\\n        List<String> recursiveFiles = []\\n        root.eachFileRecurse(FileType.FILES) { Path path -> recursiveFiles << root.relativize(path).toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['child/alpha.txt', 'child/skip.log', 'other/beta.txt', 'top.txt'], normalizeAndSort(recursiveFiles))\\n\\n        List<String> recursiveDirs = []\\n        root.eachDirRecurse { Path path -> recursiveDirs << root.relativize(path).toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['child', 'other'], normalizeAndSort(recursiveDirs))\\n\\n        List<String> matchedFiles = []\\n        child.eachFileMatch(FileType.FILES, ~/.*\\\\.txt/) { Path path -> matchedFiles << path.fileName.toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['alpha.txt'], matchedFiles)\\n\\n        List<String> matchedDirs = []\\n        root.eachDirMatch(~/o.*/) { Path path -> matchedDirs << path.fileName.toString() }\\n        assertEquals(['other'], matchedDirs)\\n\\n        List<String> traversed = []\\n        root.traverse(type: FileType.FILES, nameFilter: ~/.*\\\\.txt/) { Path path ->\\n            traversed << root.relativize(path).toString()\\n        }\\n        assertEquals(['child/alpha.txt', 'other/beta.txt', 'top.txt'], normalizeAndSort(traversed))\\n    }\\n\\n    @Test\\n    void managesDirectoriesAndRenamesUsingPathExtensionMethods(@TempDir Path tempDir) {\\n        Path nested = tempDir.resolve('parents/child/file.txt')\\n        assertSame(nested, nested.createParentDirectories())\\n        nested.text = 'created'\\n        assertTrue(Files.isDirectory(nested.parent))\\n        assertEquals('created', nested.text)\\n\\n        Path original = tempDir.resolve('original.txt')\\n        Path renamed = tempDir.resolve('renamed.txt')\\n        original.text = 'rename me'\\n        assertTrue(original.renameTo(renamed.toString()))\\n        assertFalse(Files.exists(original))\\n        assertEquals('rename me', renamed.text)\\n\\n        Path deleteRoot = tempDir.resolve('delete-me')\\n        Files.createDirectories(deleteRoot.resolve('nested'))\\n        deleteRoot.resolve('nested/file.txt').text = 'remove'\\n        assertTrue(deleteRoot.deleteDir())\\n        assertFalse(Files.exists(deleteRoot))\\n        assertTrue(tempDir.resolve('missing').deleteDir())\\n        assertFalse(renamed.deleteDir())\\n    }\\n\\n    private static List<String> normalizeAndSort(List<String> values) {\\n        values.collect { String value -> value.replace(File.separatorChar, '/' as char) }.sort()\\n    }\\n}\\n\"}\n16966:[recv] {\"type\": \"message_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering file operations**\\n\\nI'm thinking about using the `rm` command in bash for file operations. That seems okay, especially for modifying and deleting files. I need to make sure to avoid duplicates, so I'll delete any existing placeholder or replaced file. I wonder how to manage top-level files to ensure a one-to-one correspondence with the two classes. This approach feels solid, but I want to be careful and thorough in my process!\\n\\n**Organizing files**\\n\\nI need to make sure the file package is consistent, using public classes without the dollar sign. I think creating two files is the way to go here. I could use bash to create the directories, but it seems unnecessary, so Iā€™ll focus on writing the new files instead. If I need to remove any files later, Iā€™ll use the rm command. This all feels pretty straightforward!\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_002e273752b5cc99016a11339b7fb88194936e7e4f95e07d7c\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqETOkVZVVsUeDRLSy215_TxYG5IcZUC66dfLkJbWzNvWgt-P5jhqxljUEWJjbbbvz8bN5rItLRzcXBv9vjSGiK_JZKYTnJszUFQHLH9JGfDBbrqoLADufoEP9ex5NgbONvgUW8Otrq0XLHkUaCWvVvnDTL4m2r25E53EA5HzdtOdUKX7Oj0oW54VFeGJEi9SKP-6zTCPtdKT-TCjuEyQSQWAtgDF9M5YmLccEDL6hfY46OIhfwoINRJp11HRofiDjCrBroFAkE67BF0frBX03MyLCETEEtvyPNCCUSjOc95RoBHcnRSM58Y4bNl7Z9PfbjHEqRWIFgNc0BgLcMIf6S1ImbNXLGTv4ceCljkbplRsAsaVneRKcGcGnlRuP7YMjAuNpAUEjj3tk6iDrGj7qyxj9iviv9DIITvZIdpEmL5vOCi8tcDyUY-LdLuhuKs1-z5W8L84ylIIsaRltURCiAoZ6Eqgt_RySu4DSeibt3uhKphVghvpEYqHvJtKWqb7LNIc6RZtyMtCGglbIX_viCqJYSXd7uSCs7KO0n7fMowbR3veQ8TBagmU3aFE63XeqWaRcFIstefBJvhPH7k0LrCkOQbdkvoPyI0xIm-3oXEjtLPBLDtFqpqkQ1TCNJtiAFrEz_OBTjUuHvLWQElEj9DP1LB6Sl167D3kBLWgyP0KS_ym0BpKVrA8JUjRGLh1LRxkAIE1ZBKihHJdnlS5ngpGQB8ajCUsMBFkTv3Vo_w_Xlq6mnkNwiMUqj0xGjQEZpMfIsXnVqEiDLDgLhaICbQUizf3krNiSvnB8aBb6E9jISMcz5W5EwcXETkAwpSwTRwIN54ung1uzJrGBQLMPiywaYslytqTjxcPSMdVge_tQaKssHEf65U6JA3HMDo7QEhOMus1FYc-rDLd-sn7gQuTPmaKXx6y_TSWggyTpF2TJE_g9eFffVP0S59GF8U-7sAXN0JqKnq_2ilWH2kTl_cOP37nVcTsY99A4gdWV83qo9fRgc6NDgehrDDLSOvkdFIhvT3jYNo4s-st_yWSYkluNnyXtq3VptmkTfIUFkFpuFveAa1hHml18OziRq2l1jaAx-4mREAWCyaLpuIhi2qdChBSOg7F-LlsBl1rYo2zCufhPwVHx8-oPotmqMr5aW-gBuEML94fLXyUL35Xa-kOMp9K3L9hbRP1mDxR7gij4h0z2Umw2WEcmD6wF65sodJruW6xPL4FINWGs_0qdpmkyC-v9BiLXBsukQH3OpGmq-TzeRasHQDoTz48C0gEa8LcKi700USkfmk8XlN_u_1IEJ0GY-jt1